title: June 2026 Tor News
---
body:

In this month's newsletter we're highlighting the people, projects, and
practical experiments helping keep the internet open, private, and resilient.
You'll find stories from the Tor community, including a student's experience
setting up a relay on a university network in Taiwan, reflections from a recent
community gathering in Denmark, and a new participatory funding campaign
designed to support the broader Tor ecosystem at a moment of systemic funding
instability.

## Setting up a Tor relay at National Taiwan Normal University: a practical experience

A computer science student at National Taiwan Normal University successfully
set up a Tor relay on campus by working within institutional
processes—communicating with administrators, completing paperwork, and
explaining the difference between relays and exit nodes. This guest post from
anoni.net shares practical advice for deploying Tor relays on university
networks.  Here's how he did it:
https://blog.torproject.org/setting-up-tor-university-relay-taiwan/

## 3 days of fun with Tor

The Tor community organized a second gathering at Hylkedam, Denmark, building
on lessons from the first event with minimal planning and a mix of structured
and unstructured sessions. Despite a smaller group, new contributors and
ongoing projects led to productive collaboration, and we hope to expand future
meetings with broader participation and new venues. Let us know if you'd like
to participate!  Read the recap here:
https://blog.torproject.org/tor-community-gathering-2026/

## A new way to fund internet freedom

Tor is strongest when the broader internet freedom ecosystem is healthy. A
coalition of privacy, internet freedom, cryptocurrency and open-source
ecosystems, led by the Tor Project and Funding the Commons, is supporting
critical digital infrastructure with a new participatory funding campaign.
Find out more here: https://blog.torproject.org/fund-internet-freedom/

### A Server That Forgets: Exploring Stateless Relays (Osservatorio Nessuno)

Diskless operating systems can improve relay security with a focus on software
integrity and physical attack resistance. [This work and guest post is by
Osservatorio Nessuno](https://blog.torproject.org/exploring-stateless-relays/)
who run exit relays in Italy.

### OONI: Defending the public's right to know

Fighting internet censorship requires more than noticing when it happens. It
requires documenting it, sharing evidence, and building the collective capacity
to respond. [OONI](https://ooni.org/) [makes that
possible.](https://blog.torproject.org/Defending-the-right-to-know/)

### Preserving evidence: How OpenArchive fosters accountability and media sovereignty

Handling mobile media that documents human rights violations can put those
brave enough to capture a record -- and those very records -- at risk.
OpenArchive's free open source [Save app](https://www.open-archive.org/save)
and [DWeb Storage](https://www.open-archive.org/news/oa-hypha-white-paper) help
communities securely archive, verify, and encrypt this documentation without
depending on centralized platforms that can remove, lose, or expose sensitive
data at a moment's notice. [Find out
how.](https://blog.torproject.org/preserving-evidence-openarchive-fosters-accountability-media-sovereignty/)

### Supporting those who speak out (Ricochet Refresh)

[The digital threats faced by defenders of truth and democracy are
multiplying.](https://blog.torproject.org/supporting-those-who-speak-out/) So
should the capacity to respond to them. Through [tools like Ricochet
Refresh](https://www.ricochetrefresh.net/) and cybersecurity training across
lower- and middle-income countries, [Blueprint for Free
Speech](https://www.blueprintforfreespeech.net/) helps people communicate
anonymously, protect sensitive information, and continue public-interest work
more safely.

### Paskoocheh: When you need a tool to reach the tool

Access alone is not enough. Technology is only useful if people trust it,
understand how to use it safely, and can rely on support networks when digital
spaces become unstable or dangerous. [ASL19](https://asl19.org/en)'s
[Paskoocheh](http://paskoocheh.com/) [helps people in Iran access trusted
privacy and circumvention
tools](https://blog.torproject.org/when-you-need-a-tool-to-reach-the-tool-Paskoocheh/)
when websites and apps, VPNs, and app stores themselves are blocked.

### Keeping the doors open (Unredacted)

Anti-censorship tools are only as powerful as their ability to keep running.
When the door to the open internet gets slammed shut,
[Unredacted](https://unredacted.org/) builds another one. [Here's
how!](https://blog.torproject.org/keeping-the-doors-open-unredacted/)

# Keeping up with the latest releases

New Release: [Tor Browser 15.0.15](https://blog.torproject.org/new-release-tor-browser-15015/), June 3, 2026

New Release: [Tails 7.8.1](https://blog.torproject.org/new-release-tails-7_8_1/), June 4, 2026

New Alpha Release: [Tor Browser 16.0a7](https://blog.torproject.org/new-alpha-release-tor-browser-160a7/), June 3, 2026

Arti 2.4.0 released: [Relay and directory authority development; flowctl-cc stable](https://blog.torproject.org/arti_2_4_0_released/), June 1, 2026

